"Acrani G.O., Gomes R., Proença-Módena J.L., da Silva A.F., Oliveira Carminati P., Silva M.L., Santos R.I.M., Arruda E.","Apoptosis induced by Oropouche virus infection in HeLa cells is dependent on virus protein expression",2010,"Virus Research","149","1",,"56","63",,,10.1016/j.virusres.2009.12.013,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77549086113&partnerID=40&md5=63f764ed13c629f9ca99246558819c0d","Department of Cell and Molecular Biology, University of Sao Paulo School of Medicine, 3900, Av Bandeirantes, Ribeirão Preto, SP 14049-900, Brazil; Department of Genetics, University of Sao Paulo School of Medicine, 3900, Av Bandeirantes, Ribeirão Preto, SP 14049-900, Brazil","Acrani, G.O., Department of Cell and Molecular Biology, University of Sao Paulo School of Medicine, 3900, Av Bandeirantes, Ribeirão Preto, SP 14049-900, Brazil; Gomes, R., Department of Cell and Molecular Biology, University of Sao Paulo School of Medicine, 3900, Av Bandeirantes, Ribeirão Preto, SP 14049-900, Brazil; Proença-Módena, J.L., Department of Cell and Molecular Biology, University of Sao Paulo School of Medicine, 3900, Av Bandeirantes, Ribeirão Preto, SP 14049-900, Brazil; da Silva, A.F., Department of Cell and Molecular Biology, University of Sao Paulo School of Medicine, 3900, Av Bandeirantes, Ribeirão Preto, SP 14049-900, Brazil; Oliveira Carminati, P., Department of Genetics, University of Sao Paulo School of Medicine, 3900, Av Bandeirantes, Ribeirão Preto, SP 14049-900, Brazil; Silva, M.L., Department of Cell and Molecular Biology, University of Sao Paulo School of Medicine, 3900, Av Bandeirantes, Ribeirão Preto, SP 14049-900, Brazil; Santos, R.I.M., Department of Cell and Molecular Biology, University of Sao Paulo School of Medicine, 3900, Av Bandeirantes, Ribeirão Preto, SP 14049-900, Brazil; Arruda, E., Department of Cell and Molecular Biology, University of Sao Paulo School of Medicine, 3900, Av Bandeirantes, Ribeirão Preto, SP 14049-900, Brazil","Oropouche (OROV) is a single-stranded RNA arbovirus of the family Bunyaviridae, genus Orthobunyavirus, which has caused over half a million cases of febrile illness in Brazil in the past 30 years. OROV fever has been registered almost exclusively in the Amazon region, but global warming, deforestation and redistribution of vectors and animal reservoirs increases the risk of Oropouche virus emergence in other areas. OROV causes a cytolytical infection in cultured cells with characteristic cytopathic effect 48 h post-infection. We have studied the mechanisms of apoptosis induced by OROV in HeLa cells and found that OROV causes DNA fragmentation detectable by gel electrophoresis and by flow cytometric analysis of the Sub-G1 population at 36 h post-infection. Mitochondrial release of cytochrome C and activation of caspases 9 and 3 were also detected by western blot analysis. Lack of apoptosis induced by UV-inactivated OROV reveals that virus-receptor binding is not sufficient to induce cell death. Results obtained in cells treated with chloroquine and cycloheximide indicated that viral uncoating and replication are required for apoptosis induction by OROV. Furthermore, treatment of the cells with pan-caspase inhibitor prevented OROV-induced apoptosis without affecting virus progeny production. The results show that OROV infection in vitro causes apoptosis by an intracellular pathway involving mitochondria, and activated by a mechanism dependent on viral replication and protein synthesis. © 2010 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.","Apoptosis; Arbovirus; Bunyaviridae; Caspase inhibition; Emerging viruses; Oropouche virus","caspase 3; caspase 9; caspase inhibitor; chloroquine; cycloheximide; cytochrome c; dactinomycin; oncolytic arbovirus; oncolytic virus; unclassified drug; virus protein; apoptosis; Arbovirus; article; cell death; controlled study; cytopathogenic effect; DNA fragmentation; enzyme activation; enzyme inhibition; flow cytometry; gel electrophoresis; HeLa cell; human; human cell; in vitro study; mitochondrion; oropouche bunyavirus; priority journal; progeny; protein expression; protein synthesis; ultraviolet radiation; virus attachment; virus entry; virus expression; virus infection; virus replication; virus titration; Western blotting; Apoptosis; Caspase 3; Caspase 9; Cytochromes c; Cytoplasm; DNA Fragmentation; Hela Cells; Humans; Orthobunyavirus; Viral Proteins; Virulence Factors; Animalia; Arbovirus; Bunyaviridae; Oropouche virus; Orthobunyavirus",,"caspase 3, 169592-56-7; caspase 9, 180189-96-2; chloroquine, 132-73-0, 3545-67-3, 50-63-5, 54-05-7; cycloheximide, 642-81-9, 66-81-9; cytochrome c, 9007-43-6, 9064-84-0; dactinomycin, 1402-38-6, 1402-58-0, 50-76-0; Caspase 3, 3.4.22.-; Caspase 9, 3.4.22.-; Cytochromes c, 9007-43-6; Viral Proteins; Virulence Factors",,,,"Aubert, M., O'Toole, J., Blaho, J.A., Induction and prevention of apoptosis in human HEp-2 cells by herpes simplex virus type 1 (1999) J. Virol., 73, pp. 10359-10370; Ausubel, F.A.C., (2003) Current Protocols in Molecular Biology, , John Wiley and Sons; Blakqori, G., Weber, F., Efficient cDNA-based rescue of La Crosse bunyaviruses expressing or lacking the nonstructural protein NSs (2005) J. Virol., 79, pp. 10420-10428; Blakqori, G., Delhaye, S., Habjan, M., Blair, C.D., Sanchez-Vargas, I., Olson, K.E., Attarzadeh-Yazdi, G., Weber, F., La Crosse bunyavirus nonstructural protein NSs serves to suppress the type I interferon system of mammalian hosts (2007) J. Virol., 81, pp. 4991-4999; Bridgen, A., Weber, F., Fazakerley, J.K., Elliott, R.M., Bunyamwera bunyavirus nonstructural protein NSs is a nonessential gene product that contributes to viral pathogenesis (2001) Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A., 98, pp. 664-669; Brojatsch, J., Naughton, J., Rolls, M.M., Zingler, K., Young, J.A., CAR1, a TNFR-related protein, is a cellular receptor for cytopathic avian leukosis-sarcoma viruses and mediates apoptosis (1996) Cell, 87, pp. 845-855; Carrascosa, A.L., Bustos, M.J., Nogal, M.L., Gonz